{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6bab7b97-1974-47db-8c75-37de76d25cea","content":"I found **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns** in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Expensive Recursive Glob (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the **entire directory tree** at evaluation time. As the repo grows (especially if `node_modules`, `.git`, or large output folders exist), this becomes very slow. **Fix:** scope the glob to specific extensions/directories, or add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes` early.\n\n### 2. File I/O Property Function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n`System.IO.File::ReadAllText` performs **disk I/O during property evaluation**, blocking the entire evaluation pipeline. This is one of the most expensive things you can do in evaluation. **Fix:** move file reading to a target that runs at build time (e.g., a `ReadLinesFromFile` task), or remove it entirely.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (line 6 → 3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds an evaluation pass. At 3 levels this is manageable, but it's a pattern that compounds quickly. **Fix:** flatten into fewer files, or consolidate into `Directory.Build.props`.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order:** #2 (I/O during eval) > #1 (unbounded glob) > #3 (import depth). Issues #1 and #2 will scale poorly and are the most impactful to fix.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"709e456d-6dc4-4c9a-987a-0aab78ed38a5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a full picture of the project. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues:\n\n1. **Expensive glob pattern** (`**\\*.*`) - The `AdditionalFiles` item uses a deep recursive glob that walks the entire directory tree. This is expensive, especially if there are large directories like `node_modules`, `.git`, etc.\n\n2. **File I/O property function** (`$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))`) - Reading file contents during evaluation is expensive. This happens during the property evaluation phase, blocking the build.\n\n3. **Deep import chain** - `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props` - A 3-level deep import chain. \n\nThe nested imports aren't terrible on their own, but this pattern tends to compound as projects grow, and each additional layer adds overhead to the evaluation phase.","outputTokens":643,"requestId":"1411:1B1DA8:5D0ACB0:68941B8:69EC1683"},"id":"c986e549-799c-4842-8d80-48a5539e49a2","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:19:14.548Z","parentId":"0bbfc6d2-5b41-4d5e-8e72-73b15fc4ce4d"}
